<iframe src=\"javascript:false\" title=\"\" style=\"width: 0px; height: 0px; border: 0px; display: none;\"></iframe><script async=\"\" src=\"//cdn.taboola.com/libtrc/unip/1157224/tfa.js\" id=\"tb_tfa_script\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\" async=\"\" src=\"https://www.gstatic.com/recaptcha/releases/61bII03-TtCmSUR7dw9MJF9q/recaptcha__en.js\"></script><script async=\"\" src=\"//cdn.krxd.net/ctjs/controltag.js.05f9d0dad02f8a1b0b028b868bc3a3e2\"></script><script data-schema=\"NewsArticle\" type=\"application/ld+json\">{\"@context\":\"http://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"NewsArticle\",\"mainEntityOfPage\":{\"@type\":\"WebPage\",\"@id\":\"https://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-md-leap-week-calendar-20200221-f4fuin3hnvgetlzodlugbjnxfq-story.html\"},\"headline\":\"Get rid of leap days and start every year on a Monday: Johns Hopkins professors propose a new calendar\",\"url\":\"https://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-md-leap-week-calendar-20200221-f4fuin3hnvgetlzodlugbjnxfq-story.html\",\"thumbnailUrl\":\"\",\"isAccessibleForFree\":\"False\",\"hasPart\":{\"@type\":\"WebPageElement\",\"isAccessibleForFree\":\"False\",\"cssSelector\":\".pb-f-article-body\"},\"image\":{\"@type\":\"ImageObject\",\"url\":\"https://www.baltimoresun.com/resizer/L9AoF1N0cEh9j4z7NWXYnUEf19Y=/1200x0/top/arc-anglerfish-arc2-prod-tronc.s3.amazonaws.com/public/VV3DQVKOEZG45BIKBLE4AXBDZM.jpg\",\"height\":3845.0,\"width\":1200},\"articleSection\":\"business\",\"dateCreated\":\"2020-02-14T20:14:18.219Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2020-02-24T16:08:21.925Z\",\"dateModified\":\"2020-02-24T16:08:21.869Z\",\"articleBody\":\"In 1582, Pope Gregory began a campaign to replace Julius Caesar\u2019s widely used calendar with a slightly more accurate one that was named for him. Most of the modern world eventually agreed, and the rest is history.Now a pair of Johns Hopkins professors believe it\u2019s time to turn the page on the Gregorian calendar in favor of one to really last the ages.\u201cYou don\u2019t ever have to buy a new calendar,\u201d said Steve H. Hanke, a Johns Hopkins University economist who partnered with Hopkins astrophysicist Richard Conn Henry on the Hanke-Henry Permanent Calendar, which would not change from year to year.\u201cHow much needless work do institutions, such as companies and universities, put into arranging their calendars for every coming year? From now on, they could do it once, and it is done forevermore.\u201dThe idea is simple: Start every year on Monday, Jan. 1. Every other day would fall on the same day every year.Change would be \u201cno problem,\u201d he said, just like Canada\u2019s switch to the metric system. (No comment on the failed U.S. moves to go metric.)The benefits would be many: Holidays except for the Fourth of July and Thanksgiving would be observed on a Monday, creating regular long weekends and fewer midweek disruptions.There would be no battles over the start to the school year or sports seasons and less fretting at corporations over bookkeeping and planning. There would never be another Friday the 13th. (Sorry, Jason.)Every year would just repeat in a Groundhog Day movie kind of way, only over a year, which would be 364 days rather than 365.But how? Hanke said President Donald Trump could issue an executive order. The U.S. government would switch, and the states and other countries would follow.The White House did not respond to a request for comment. But Hanke is confident that Trump, known for branding, would come around to having his name on a calendar for the next four centuries or longer. He could bump a pope and Caesar.It\u2019s the latest bet for the rather dated idea from the professors, who came up with it years ago. Using new calendars year after year to redo the syllabus became a drag.Others have pitched permanent calendars, though most failed for proposing to drop the seven-day week, which would mean violating the commandment about resting on the Sabbath. The League of Nations came close but rejected a permanent calendar in 1937 because of this.Most also were a little off, time-wise, even more so than the Gregorian, which requires a leap year every four years. That adds an extra day to February \u2014 as it does this year \u2014 to keep the seasons in sync.The Hanke-Henry calendar would make 2020 the last of those leaps. But they would add a week to their calendar every five or six years to keep up with the 365.24 days it take the Earth to orbit the sun.It\u2019s unclear what would happen to the paper calendar and planner industry, with sales remaining in the hundreds of millions of dollars annually despite the digital age.An annual $15 calendar featuring Orioles baseball team members with their pets has helped raise more than $370,000 over eight years for the Baltimore Animal Rescue and Care Shelter.Bailey Deacon, a BARCS spokeswoman, said she still sees new puppies and kitties getting their month \u2014 as well as new Orioles.\u201cThose who truly use paper calendars are marking them up each year with their appointments, meetings and occasions, so I would think they would eventually need a clean slate each January,\u201d she said.The corporate world that yearns for stability and efficiency also could hugely benefit, according to Hanke\u2019s research.Observing holidays on Mondays would save an estimated $575 per person a year in productivity costs. There would be fewer bookkeeping issues, including reduction in errors related to something called the \u201cday count,\u201d which calculates interest on bonds and other investments, and are now a $130 billion problem.So, would business types make a date for change?No, said Brent Goldfarb, associate professor of management and entrepreneurship in the University of Maryland\u2019s Smith School of Business.\u201cWhatever the merits of this calendar, it is not practically important,\u201d said Goldfarb, co-author of the 2019 book \u201cBubbles and Crashes: The Boom and Bust of Technological Innovation.\u201d\u201cIt is extraordinarily difficult to change these sorts of conventions without some sort of government coercion, and even then, it is hard,\u201d Goldfarb said. \u201cJust as the United States was unable to shift to the metric system, I see little chance that we\u2019d change all our calendars, computer programs, and intuitive thinking to get rid of leap years and have a constant calendar.\u201dHanke and Henry are not to be deterred. Next they want to eliminate time zones and put everyone on the same clock.\",\"creator\":[\"Meredith Cohn \"],\"author\":[{\"@type\":\"Person\",\"name\":\"Meredith Cohn \"}],\"keywords\":[],\"publisher\":{\n        \"@type\": \"Organization\",\n        \"name\": \"Baltimore Sun\",\n        \"logo\": {\n          \"@type\": \"ImageObject\",\n          \"url\": professors believe a new, permanent calendar, perhaps named for President Trump, would be a lot more simple.\"}</script> <script data-schema=\"Organization\" Most of the modern world eventually agreed, and the rest is history.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>Now a pair of Johns Hopkins Steve H. Hanke, a Johns Hopkins University economist who partnered with Hopkins astrophysicist Richard Conn Henry on the Hanke-Henry Permanent Calendar, which would not change from year to year.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>\u201cHow much needless work do institutions, such as companies and universities, put into arranging their calendars for every coming year? From now on, they could do it once, and it is done forevermore.\u201d</p> </div></div> <div class=\"desktop-nativo mobile-yieldmo inline-ad \" data-inline-ad-count=\"2\"> <span class=\"hidden-desktop\"> <div class=\"wrapper clearfix col pb-feature pb-layout-item pb-f-ads-yieldmo\" data-pb-name=\"Yieldmo Ad\" data-pb-curated=\"curated\" data-pb-id=\"unnamed-feature\" id=\"\"> <div id=\"ym_1885667251538527982\"></div> <script>window.serviceCallbacks.push(function(){if(DeviceDetection.any()&&UrlParams.isVendorEnabled(\"yieldmo\")){var el=document.getElementById(\"ym_1885667251538527982\");if(false)lazyLoadService.addPendingObject({id:\"ym_1885667251538527982\",el:el,load:function(){YieldmoService.load({id:\"ym_1885667251538527982\",el:el})}});else YieldmoService.load({id:\"ym_1885667251538527982\",el:el})}});</script> </div></span> <span class=\"hidden-mobile\"><div class=\"wrapper clearfix full pb-feature pb-layout-item pb-f-ads-nativo\" data-pb-name=\"Nativo Ad\" data-pb-curated=\"curated\" data-pb-id=\"unnamed-feature\" id=\"fnm2621lYw13Sr\"> <div id=\"998\" class=\"trb_ar_nt\"> </div> </div></span> </div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>The idea is simple: Start every year on Monday, Jan. 1. Every other day would fall on the same day every year.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"interstitial_link\" class=\"crd clln--it\" data-interstitial=\"auto\"> <div class=\"crd--cnt\"> <span class=\"roadblock\"> <strong><a href=\"https://www.baltimoresun.com/health/bs-hs-coronavirus-prep-in-maryland-20200229-wgynczjx2fcahj5gksac73sfyu-story.html#nt=interstitial-auto\">[Most read] Maryland preparing for possible extended shutdowns of schools, businesses, events as coronavirus spreads <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u00bb</span></a></strong> </span> </div></div><div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>Change would be \u201cno problem,\u201d he said, just like Canada\u2019s switch to the metric system. (No comment on the failed U.S. moves to go metric.)</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>The benefits would be many: Holidays except for the Fourth of July and Thanksgiving would be observed on a Monday, creating regular long weekends and fewer midweek disruptions.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>There would be no battles over the start to the school year or sports seasons and less fretting at corporations over bookkeeping and planning. There would never be another Friday the 13th. (Sorry, Jason.)</p> </div></div> <div class=\"mobile-nativo inline-ad hidden-desktop\" data-inline-ad-count=\"3\"> <div class=\"wrapper clearfix full pb-feature pb-layout-item pb-f-ads-nativo\" data-pb-name=\"Nativo Ad\" data-pb-curated=\"curated\" data-pb-id=\"unnamed-feature\" id=\"f0thgVlHYw13Sr\"> <div id=\"19603\" class=\"trb_ar_nt\"> </div> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>Every year would just repeat in a Groundhog Day movie kind of way, only over a year, which would be 364 days rather than 365.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>But how? Hanke said President Donald Trump could issue an executive order. The U.S. government would switch, and the states and other countries would follow.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"interstitial_link\" class=\"crd clln--it\" data-interstitial=\"auto\"> <div class=\"crd--cnt\"> <span class=\"roadblock\"> <strong><a href=\"https://www.baltimoresun.com/health/bs-md-hogan-coronavirus-presser-20200227-3m3p2otzjjb5tl2qlfdnqayqai-story.html#nt=interstitial-auto\">[Most read] Maryland tests three new patients for possible cases of coronavirus; Gov. Hogan says he\u2019ll request $10M for preparedness <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u00bb</span></a></strong> </span> </div></div><div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>The White House did not respond to a request for comment. But Hanke is confident that Trump, known for branding, would come around to having his name on a calendar for the next four centuries or longer. He could bump a pope and Caesar.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>It\u2019s the latest bet for the rather dated idea from the professors, who came up with it years ago. Using new calendars year after year to redo the syllabus became a drag.</p> </div></div> <div class=\"mobile-yieldmo inline-ad hidden-desktop\" data-inline-ad-count=\"4\"> <div class=\"wrapper clearfix col pb-feature pb-layout-item pb-f-ads-yieldmo\" data-pb-name=\"Yieldmo Ad\" data-pb-curated=\"curated\" data-pb-id=\"unnamed-feature\" id=\"\"> <div id=\"ym_1000072\"></div> <script>window.serviceCallbacks.push(function(){if(DeviceDetection.any()&&UrlParams.isVendorEnabled(\"yieldmo\")){var el=document.getElementById(\"ym_1000072\");if(true)lazyLoadService.addPendingObject({id:\"ym_1000072\",el:el,load:function(){YieldmoService.load({id:\"ym_1000072\",el:el})}});else YieldmoService.load({id:\"ym_1000072\",el:el})}});</script> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p data-item-type=\"depthscroll\" data-item-id=\"depth_scroll_middle\" data-item-number=\"middle\">Others have pitched permanent calendars, though most failed for proposing to drop the seven-day week, which would mean violating the commandment about resting on the Sabbath. The League of Nations came close but rejected a permanent calendar in 1937 because of this.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>Most also were a little off, time-wise, even more so than the Gregorian, which requires a leap year every four years. That adds an extra day to February \u2014 as it does this year \u2014 to keep the seasons in sync.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>The Hanke-Henry calendar would make 2020 the last of those leaps. But they would add a week to their calendar every five or six years to keep up with the 365.24 days it take the Earth to orbit the sun.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"interstitial_link\" class=\"crd clln--it\" data-interstitial=\"auto\"> <div class=\"crd--cnt\"> <span class=\"roadblock\"> <strong><a href=\"https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/crime/bs-md-ci-cr-singleton-duppins-murder-charge-20200302-rfjv2x66ujfhbnkwffug5o5jfe-story.html#nt=interstitial-auto\">[Most read] 19-year-old charged with murder in Friday shooting in Northeast Baltimore <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u00bb</span></a></strong> </span> </div></div><div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>It\u2019s unclear what would happen to the paper calendar and planner industry, with sales remaining in the hundreds of millions of dollars annually despite the digital age.</p> </div></div> <div capitalized\">The Evening Sun Newsletter</h2> </div> <div class=\"caption-text\">Daily</div> <div> <hr class=\"\"> </div> <div class=\"preview-text\">Get your evening news in your e-mail inbox. There would be fewer bookkeeping issues, including reduction in errors related to something called the \u201cday count,\u201d which calculates interest on bonds and other investments, and are now a $130 billion problem.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>So, would business types make a date for change?</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>No, said Brent Goldfarb, associate professor of management and entrepreneurship in the University of Maryland\u2019s Smith School of Business.</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p class=\"stop-here\" data-role=\"intersectionobserver\">\u201cWhatever the merits of this calendar, it is not practically important,\u201d said Goldfarb, co-author of the 2019 book \u201cBubbles and Crashes: The Boom and Bust of Technological Innovation.\u201d</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"text\" class=\"crd clln--it\"> <div class=\" crd--cnt \"> <p>\u201cIt is extraordinarily difficult to change these sorts of conventions without some sort of government coercion, and even then, it is hard,\u201d Goldfarb said. \u201cJust as the United States was unable to shift to the metric system, I see little chance that we\u2019d change all our calendars, computer programs, and intuitive thinking to get rid of leap years and have a constant calendar.\u201d</p> </div></div> <div data-type=\"recommender\" data-pb-id=\"in-body-recommender\" class=\"crd clln--it \"> <div data-item-type=\"depthscroll\" data-item-id=\"depth_scroll_bottom\" data-item-number=\"bottom\">Hanke and Henry are not to be deterred. Next they want to eliminate time zones and put everyone on the same clock.</p> <div class=\"spaced spaced-md spaced-bottom hidden-mobile\"></div> <div class=\"spaced spaced-sm spaced-bottom
